  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Preparedness and response to primary and secondary impacts of  COVID-19 on IDPs in Benue State</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Benue state is currently challenged with a complex emergency which includes violent conflict, social inequalities and underlying poverty exacerbated by natural hazards including flood and diseases such as HIV/AIDS, malaria and other health conditions such as malnutrition. The state has just recovered from a flood emergency which hit many LGAs between August and October 2019 and currently combating the heightened insecurity as a result of the violent conflicts involving herders and farmers. The underlying factors have contributed to the widespread displacement witnessed across the state leaving over 400,000 IDPs across the state largely in Agatu, Guma, Makurdi, Oju LGAs, and over 7,000 refugees in Kwande LGA from Cameroon. The State currently has 430 confirmed cases of COVID-19 with 139 recovered and 9 fatalities. This is also added to the recurring health challenges from lasar fever and a water-borne disease which has been ravaging communities in the state since December 2019. With state government being overwhelmed, the very agrarian communities of Benue state who contribute largely to the food production in Nigeria require support to overcome the  impacts of the COVID-19.</narrative>
  </description>
